Throughout Bolivia, a land without sea, they still vividly remember the coast lost before Chile in a bloody conflict over the resources that took place in the 19th century, in addition to the longing to sail back through the Pacific Ocean.
These hopes may be the greatest in decades, as Bolivia expects a resolution of the International Court of Justice by 1 October, after five years of discussion.
"Bolivia has the impulse, a spirit of unity and serenity and, of course, is waiting for the result with a positive vision," said Roberto Calzadilla, a Bolivian diplomat.
Many Bolivians will observe the ruling of the International Court of Justice on large screens distributed throughout the country, in the hope that the Hague court will rule in favor of Bolivia's claim that, after decades of intermittent talks, Chile has an obligation to negotiate to grant Bolivia a sovereign exit to the sea.
Evo Morales, the charismatic indigenous president of Bolivia, who wages a controversial battle for re-election next year, also has much to say about the resolution of Monday.
"We are very close to returning to the Pacific Ocean," he promised at the end of August.
However, some analysts believe that it is unlikely that the court would decide in favor of Bolivia and that the situation would change little if it did.
The United Nations agency based in the Netherlands has no authority to award Chilean territory and has stipulated that it will not determine the outcome of possible talks.
The fact that the International Court of Justice resolution arrives only six months after the final allegations indicates that the case "was not complicated," said Paz Zárate, a Chilean expert in international law.
Far from promoting the cause of Bolivia, it may have been hindered in the last four years.
"The problem of access to the sea has been kidnapped by the current Bolivian administration," Zárate said.
In addition, he suggested that Morales' belligerent rhetoric has undermined any residual Chilean goodwill.
Bolivia and Chile will continue to talk at some point, but it will be extremely difficult to hold conversations after this.
Both countries have not exchanged ambassadors since 1962.
Former President Eduardo Rodríguez Veltze, representative of Bolivia in The Hague, rejected the idea that court decision-making was unusually rapid.
On Monday, Bolivia will be offered "an extraordinary opportunity to open a new era of relations with Chile" and the possibility of "ending 139 years of disagreements with mutual benefits," he said.
Calzadilla also denied that Morales, who is still one of the most popular presidents of Latin America, used the maritime issue as a political crutch.
