John Edward: Language skills are key to the citizens of the world
Scotland's independent educational centers have a history of academic excellence that has continued in 2018 with another set of extraordinary results in the exams that are reinforced by individual and collective successes harvested in the fields of sport, art, music and other community projects.
With more than 30,000 students throughout Scotland, these centres, represented by the Scottish Council of Independent Colleges (SCIS, for their acronyms in English), strive to deliver the best level of service to students and parents.
The aim of the independent schools is to prepare their students to continue their higher education studies, to the career they choose and to the place they occupy as citizens of the world.
As an educational sector that can design and implement an adapted curriculum, it is observed that modern languages remain a popular and desired subject in the centers.
As Nelson Mandela said, "If you speak to a man in a language he understands, the message comes to his head.
If you speak to him in his tongue, he comes to his heart."
This is a powerful reminder that if you want to build relationships and build trust with people from other countries, you cannot rely solely on English.
If we take into account the recent results of this year's exams, we can observe that the languages are at the top of the classification tables, being the highest approved rates in the independent schools.
In total, 68% of students who studied foreign languages obtained an A, the highest grade.
The data collected from the 74 centres that are part of the SCIS showed that 72% of students obtained an A in Mandarin, while 72% of those who studied German, 69% of those who studied French and 63% of those who studied Spanish also obtained an A.
This shows that Scotland's independent schools support foreign languages by considering them a fundamental competence that both children and young people will certainly need in the future.
At present, it is considered that, as a subject, languages are at the same level as CTIM subjects (science, technology, engineering and mathematics) in the curricula of independent schools and everywhere.
A survey carried out in 2014 by the UK Employment and Competence Commission revealed that, of the reasons given by employers about the difficulties they encountered in filling jobs, 17 % were attributed to the lack of language skills.
Therefore, language skills are increasingly indispensable in preparing young people for their future careers.
Possible job opportunities that require languages are increasing, so these skills are essential in a globalized world.
Regardless of the career someone chooses, if he has learned a second language, he will have a real advantage in the future thanks to a competition like this, which will last his whole life.
Being able to communicate directly with persons from foreign countries will allow that person to automatically advance to competition.
According to a survey conducted by YouGov among more than 4000 adults in the United Kingdom in 2013, 75% of them did not speak any foreign language well enough to maintain a conversation, and it was also established that the only language spoken by a two-digit percentage, 15%, was French.
For this reason, investing in language teaching is now important for children today.
If they know several languages, especially those of developing economies, children will be equipped to have better opportunities to find quality employment.
In Scotland, each school will teach different languages.
Some centres will focus on the most classical modern languages, while others will teach the languages considered most important for the United Kingdom by 2020, such as Mandarin or Japanese.
Whatever the interests of a child, in independent schools, you can always choose from a number of languages provided by specialized teaching staff in this field.
Scotland's independent educational centres devote all their efforts to providing a learning environment that prepares children and that teams with the skills necessary to succeed, whatever the future holds them.
At present, it is undeniable that, in a global business environment, languages continue to be of vital importance to the future of the country, so this should be reflected in education.
In fact, modern languages should be considered "competence for international communication".
Independent schools will continue to offer these options, diversity and excellence to young people in Scotland.
We have to do this.
John Edward is the director of the Scottish Council of Independent Colleges
