North Korea says that "there's no chance" of unilateral disarmament first if they don't have confidence
On Saturday, the Minister for Foreign Affairs of North Korea informed the United Nations that the continuation of sanctions deepened his mistrust in the United States and that there was no possibility that his country would unilaterally renounce nuclear weapons under these circumstances.
Ri Yong Ho declared before the annual General Assembly of the international agency that North Korea had adopted "important measures of goodwill" over the past year, such as the cessation of nuclear and missile testing, the dismantling of nuclear testing facilities and the commitment to nuclear non-proliferation and nuclear technology.
"However, we did not receive any similar response from the United States," he said.
"If we do not have confidence in the United States, we cannot have confidence in our national security, and in those circumstances there is no possibility that we might first disarm unilaterally."
Although Ri repeated the well-known complaints from North Korea about Washington's resistance to a phased denuclearization formula that rewards the country as it takes steps, his statement is important, as he did not simply reject unilateral denuclearization, as Pyongyang has done in the past.
Ri referred to a joint statement issued by Kim Jong One and Donald Trump following the first summit between an active US president and a North Korean leader on 12 June in Singapore, when Kim pledged to work for the "denuclearization of the Korean peninsula" and Trump guaranteed the security of North Korea.
North Korea has pursued the official end of the 1950-53 Korean War, but the United States has said that Pyongyang must first renounce its nuclear weaponry.
Washington has also resisted calls for the smoothing of international sanctions against North Korea.
"The United States has insisted on denuclearization in the first place and has increased pressure through sanctions in order to achieve its purpose in a coercive manner, even by raising objections to a declaration of termination of the war," Ri said.
"The idea that sanctions can make us fall on our knees is a chimera of people who don't know us.
The problem is that the continuation of sanctions deepens our mistrust."
Ri made no mention of the plans of a second summit between Kim and Trump, announced by the US leader at the beginning of the week.
Instead, the Minister highlighted three meetings between Kim and Moon Jae, South Korea's leader, in the last five months, and added: "If South Korea had been an interested part in denuclearization instead of the United States, the denuclearization of the Korean peninsula would not be found in such a stagnation."
Even so, the tone of Ri's speech was radically different from last year's speech, when he told the UN General Assembly that it was inevitable to direct North Korea's missiles to U.S. soil after the "malign president" Trump, on a suicide mission, called Kim " rocket man".
This year at the United Nations, Trump, who threatened to "fully destroy" North Korea last year, praised Kim for his courage in advancing disarmament, but said that much remained to be done and that it was necessary to continue applying sanctions until North Korea became denuclear.
On Wednesday, Trump said there was no deadline for this: "We can take two years, three years or five months, no matter."
China and Russia allege that the UN Security Council should reward Pyongyang for its progress.
However, as US Secretary of State Mike Pompeo told the UN Security Council on Thursday: "The imposition of the sanctions of the Security Council must continue forcefully and without non-compliance until we realize the ultimate and fully verified denuclearization."
The Security Council has unanimously imposed sanctions on North Korea since 2006, in an attempt to cut funding for Pyongyang ballistic and nuclear missile programmes.
Pompeo spoke with Ri outside the UN General Assembly and later commented that he would visit Pyongyang again next month to prepare a second summit.
Pompeo has already visited North Korea three times this year, but his last trip was not well.
He left Pyongyang in July saying that progress had taken place, but, a few hours later, North Korea reported that his "requirements were those of a mobster."
At a meeting with Moon this month, North Korea undertook to dismantle a missile site and a nuclear complex if the United States applied the "measures concerned".
He said Kim had told him that the "proper measures" he was looking for were the security assurances Trump had promised in Singapore and steps towards normalizing relations with Washington.
Harvard students take a course on how to rest enough
Thanks to a new course that is being taught this year at Harvard University, all university students sleep more in an attempt to fight the growing machista culture of studying all night drinking caffeine.
One professor found that students at the number one university in the world often have no idea about the basic care of themselves.
Charles Czeisler, professor of sleep medicine at Harvard School of Medicine, and a specialist at Brigham and Women's Hospital designed the course, it is believed that the first of his class in the U.S.
His motivation for starting the course arose after giving a talk about how sleep deprivation affects learning.
"At the end of the course, a girl came up and asked me why she just found out about this now, in her last year.
He said no one had ever told him about the importance of sleep, which surprised me," he told The Telegraph.
The course, first taught this year, explains to students the basic concepts of how good sleep habits contribute to academic and sports performance, as well as improving general well-being.
Paul Barreira, professor of psychiatry at Harvard School of Medicine and executive director of the health services of the university, noted that the university decided to introduce the course after discovering that the students barely slept during the week.
The one-hour course includes a series of interactive tasks.
In one section, there is an image of a bedroom, where students click on coffee cups, curtains, sports shoes and books that inform them of the effects of caffeine and light, as well as the impact of lack of sleep on sports performance and the importance of establishing a routine to go to sleep.
In another section, participants are informed how long-term sleep deprivation can increase the risk of heart attack, embolism, depression, and cancer.
A campus icon with interactive icons then encourages participants to think about their daily routines.
"We know it's not going to change students' behavior instantly.
However, we believe that they have a right to know, just like anyone else has a right to know the effects on the health of smoking tobacco," added Professor Czeisler.
He said that the culture of pride for "sleep night" still exists and added that modern technology and the increasing pressure students are subjected to meant that sleep deprivation was a growing problem.
Sleeping long enough and a dream of good quality should be the "secret weapon" of students to fight stress, fatigue and anxiety; even to avoid gaining weight, since sleep deprivation causes the brain to generate a feeling of hunger, that's why they want to eat all the time.
Raymond So, a 19-year-old Californian who studies chemical and physical biology, helped Professor Czeisler design the course after attending one of his classes the previous year during his first year at Harvard.
He pointed out that the course had opened his eyes and inspired him to expand it to the entire campus.
He hoped that the next step would be to ask all postgraduate students to complete a similar curriculum before joining the competitive institution.
The recommendation of Professor Czeisler is that students think of setting an alarm to go to bed and another to wake up, and that they be aware of the harmful effects of the "blue light" that emit the screens of electrical devices and LEDs, which can alter the circadian rhythms, so they would end up having trouble sleeping.
