The National Trust spies on the secret life of bats
This new research, which has been carried out in a state of the Scottish Highlands, tries to discover how bats use the landscape in their search for food.
All that is found is expected to shed more light on the behaviour of the only flying mammals and to help guide future conservation activities.
The study, carried out by the National Trust for Scotland, will follow the common and soprano bats, as well as the Daubenton river bats and long-eared browns of the Inverewe gardens in Wester Ross.
Special recorders will be placed in strategic locations of the property to track bat activities during the season.
The NHS staff and volunteers will also conduct mobile investigations with portable detectors.
The experts will analyze the sounds collected in the recordings to discover the frequency of bat calls and what species they do.
There will then be a report and a habitat map to create a detailed picture of the environment and its behaviour.
Rob Dewar, nature conservation consultant for NTS, hopes that the results will reveal which areas of habitat are most important for bats and how they are used by each species.
This information will determine the benefits of habitat management, such as the creation of meadows and how forests should be maintained for bats and other associated species.
The bat populations in Scotland and the United Kingdom have been considerably reduced in the last century.
They are under threat from the construction and development that affects their nests and the loss of their habitat.
Wind turbines and electrical wiring can also pose a risk to them, as can insecticide papers and other chemical treatments of construction materials or attacks of domestic cats.
The bats are not really blind,
but because of their night hunting habits, their ears are more useful than their eyes to achieve their goal.
They use a sophisticated eco-location technique that locates ants and obstacles on their flight route.
The NTS, which is responsible for the care of over 270 historic buildings, 38 important gardens and 76 000 hectares of land throughout the country, takes over the subject of bats very seriously.
He has ten trained experts in this area, who regularly conduct surveys, nest inspections and occasionally rescues.
The organization has inaugurated even the first and only reserve dedicated to bats in Scotland in the state of Threave in Dumfries and Galloway, which is home to eight of Scotland's ten bat species.
The property manager, David Thompson, says it is the ideal territory for them.
"Here, in Threat, we have a fantastic area for bats," he said.
"We have old buildings, many old trees and all the right habitat.
However, there are still many unknown things about bats, so the work we do here and in other properties will help us better understand what they need to develop."
It stresses the importance of checking for bats before carrying out maintenance tasks within the properties, since a colony of farmed animals can involuntaryly be destroyed and 400 females and offspring could be killed, which would mean annihilating a whole local population.
The bats are protected and it is illegal to kill, harass or disturb them, as well as to destroy their colonies.
Elisabeth Ferrell, the Scottish officer responsible for the Bat Conservation Trust, has encouraged the public to cooperate.
He said, "We still have a lot to learn about bats and many other species about which we don't know how their populations evolve."
