The trade war between the United States and China could benefit Beijing
The first saves from the trade war between the United States and China were deafening, and although there is still much left to end the battle, a break between countries could benefit Beijing, experts think.
Donald Trump, the President of the United States, launched the first warning earlier this year by putting tariffs on major Chinese exports, such as solar panels, steel and aluminium.
The most significant escalation took place this week with new tariffs that affect 200,000 million dollars (150,000 million pounds sterling) in products, which charges half of the products entering the United States from China.
On all occasions, Beijing has taken equivalent reprisals, recently applying five to ten percent tariffs to US products worth $60 billion.
China has committed itself to equalizing US attacks, and it is unlikely that the second most powerful economy in the world will soon loosen.
Getting Washington back would mean yielding to the demands, but publicly submitting to the United States would be too embarrassing for Chinese President Xi Jinping.
Even so, experts say that if Beijing plays its cards well, the pressures of the U.S. trade war could positively help China in the long run by reducing interdependence between the two economies.
