Syria is ready to return refugees, says Foreign Minister
Syria claims that it is ready for the voluntary return of refugees and calls for help to rebuild a country devastated by a war that has been over seven years old.
In a speech earlier by the United Nations General Assembly, Foreign Minister Walid al-Moualem said that the conditions of the country were improving.
"The situation on the ground is now more stable and secure thanks to the progress that has been made in the fight against terrorism," he said.
The government continues to rehabilitate the areas destroyed by terrorists to try to restore normality.
All conditions for the voluntary return to the country of refugees have already been established that had to abandon it because of terrorism and unilateral economic measures that affected their daily lives and livelihoods.
The UN estimates that, since the war began in 2011, more than 5.5 million Syrians have fled the country.
There are another six million people who still live in the country and need humanitarian aid.
Al-Moualem acknowledged that the Syrian regime would appreciate the help to rebuild the devastated country.
But he also stressed that he would not accept conditional assistance or assistance from the countries that promoted the insurgency.
