Update of the Red tide: Decrease concentrations in Pinellas, Manatee and Sarasota
The new report by the Florida Fish and Wildlife Commission shows a general reduction in red tide concentrations in areas of Tampa Bay area.
According to the FWC, irregular flowering conditions are being reported in areas of Pinellas, Manatee, Sarasota, Charlotte and Collier counties, suggesting a reduction in concentrations.
The flowering of the red tide extends approximately 130 miles of coastline from Pinellas County north to Lee County South.
Irregular parcels can be found about 10 miles from Hillsborough County Coast, but in fewer places if compared to last week.
Red tide has also been detected in Pasco County.
During the past week, average concentrations have been reported in Pinellas County and on its coast, concentrations between lows and highs on the Hillsborough County coast, background concentrations at highs in Manatee County, background concentrations at highs in Sarasota County and its coast, background concentrations at mediums in Charlotte County, background concentrations at highs in Lee County and at its coast, and low concentrations at Collier County.
Respiratory irritation problems continue to be reported in Pinellas, Manatee, Sarasota, Lee and Collier counties.
No respiratory irritation problems have been reported in the northwest of Florida during the past week.
